{"title_page": "Karl Widemann", "text_new": "'''Karl Widemann''' or '''Carl Widemann''' or '''Carolus Widemann''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philipneal.net/voynichsources/rudolph_manuscripts|title=Surviving alchemical manuscripts of Rudolph II|author=Philip Neal}}</ref> was a German author, physician and collector of manuscripts, from [[Augsburg]], and secretary of the English alchemist [[Edward Kelley]], at the court of Emperor [[Rudolph II]].<ref name=\"Grell\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_m1Mf52bK70C&lpg=PA164&ots=eNsmZIfvcK&dq=Paracelsus%20Widemann&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=Paracelsus%20Widemann&f=false|page=163|title=Paracelsus|year=1998|author=Ole Peter Grell}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBetween 1587 and 1588, Widemann worked in [[Prague]] for Edward Kelly at the court of Emperor Rudolph II. Widemann also worked in [[T\u0159ebo\u0148]] for the Ro\u017emberks, also known as the [[Rosenberg family]].\nKarl Widemann is known for copying and collecting over 30 years the works from [[Paracelsus]]. Because of this many unpublished works from Paracelsus survived to the present day. He did the same for the works of [[Caspar Schwenckfeld]], and Widemann's close colleagues [[Valentin Krautwald]] and [[Adam Reissner]]. After [[Helisaeus Roeslin]]'s (Helis\u00e4us R\u00f6slin) death in 1616, his unpublished astrology, theology and [[kabbalistic]] work merged into the manuscript collection of Karl Widemann. [[Adam Haslmayr]] a close friend of Widemann, wrote him a letter about [[Rosicrucianism|Rosicrucian]] people who revealed the Theophrastiam, on December 24, 1611.<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n\n==Voynich manuscript==\n{{Main|Voynich manuscript}}\nIn March 1599 Emperor Rudolph II bought books from Carl Widemann for 500 Taler. However, these books were not catalogued in Rudolph's ''Kunstkammer'' inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voynich.nu/history.html#n11|title=The history of the Voynich MS|year=2017|author=Ren\u00e9 Zandbergen}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=K\u00f6nigin Christina, ihre Bibliothekare und ihre Handschriften|author=Christian Callmer|year=1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Alchemical Manuscripts in the collections of Rudolf II. |author=A. Richterov\u00e1|year=2016|pages=249\u2013291}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Interpraetatio Mystica et Vera in Quartum librum Esdrae Prophetae'' - 1619<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n*''Paracelsi Testamentum''<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widemann, Karl}}\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century German physicians]]\n[[Category:17th-century German physicians]]\n[[Category:16th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "text_old": "'''Karl Widemann''' or '''Carl Widemann''' or '''Carolus Widemann''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philipneal.net/voynichsources/rudolph_manuscripts|title=Surviving alchemical manuscripts of Rudolph II|author=Philip Neal}}</ref> was a German author, physician and collector of manuscripts, from [[Augsburg]], and secretary of the English alchemist [[Edward Kelley]], at the court of Emperor [[Rudolph II]].<ref name=\"Grell\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_m1Mf52bK70C&lpg=PA164&ots=eNsmZIfvcK&dq=Paracelsus%20Widemann&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=Paracelsus%20Widemann&f=false|page=163|title=Paracelsus|year=1998|author=Ole Peter Grell}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBetween 1587 and 1588, Widemann worked in [[Prague]] for Edward Kelly at the court of Emperor Rudolph II. Widemann also worked in [[T\u0159ebo\u0148]] for the Ro\u017emberks, also known as the [[Rosenberg family]].\nKarl Widemann is known for copying and collecting over 30 years the works from [[Paracelsus]]. Because of this many unpublished works from Paracelsus survived to the present day. He did the same for the works of [[Caspar Schwenckfeld]], and Widemann's close colleagues [[Valentin Krautwald]] and [[Adam Reissner]]. After [[Helisaeus Roeslin]]'s (Helis\u00e4us R\u00f6slin) death in 1616, his unpublished astrology, theology and [[kabbalistic]] work merged into the manuscript collection of Karl Widemann. [[Adam Haslmayr]] a close friend of Widemann, wrote him a letter about [[Rosicrucianism|Rosicrucian]] people who revealed the Theophrastiam, on December 24, 1611.<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n\n==Voynich manuscript==\n{{Main|Voynich manuscript}}\nIn March 1599 Emperor Rudolph II bought books from Carl Widemann for 500 Taler. However, these books were not catalogued in Rudolph's ''Kunstkammer'' inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voynich.nu/history.html#n11|title=The history of the Voynich MS|year=2017|author=Ren\u00e9 Zandbergen}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=K\u00f6nigin Christina, ihre Bibliothekare und ihre Handschriften|author=Christian Callmer|year=1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Alchemical Manuscripts in the collections of Rudolf II. |author=A. Richterov\u00e1|year=2016|pages=249\u2013291}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Interpraetatio Mystica et Vera in Quartum librum Esdrae Prophetae'' - 1619<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n*''Paracelsi Testamentum''<ref name=\"Grell\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widemann, Karl}}\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century German physicians]]\n[[Category:17th-century German physicians]]\n[[Category:16th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Widemann"}
